Let $m, n$ be positive integers and let $[a]$ denote the residue class $mod 
m n$ of the integer $a$ (thus ${ [r] divides r " is an integer" }$ has exactly
$m n$ elements). Suppose the set ${ [a r] divides r " is an integer" }$ has
exactly $m$ elements. Prove that there is a positive integer $q$ such that $q$
is prime to $m n$ and $[n q] = [a]$.
